surveys.narrative: Of the six bio-dominate species in Minnesota waters, all are more abundant than the statewide median. Northern Pike, while only slightly above the statewide median in number, greatly exceed state- wide averages in weight. Tullibee numbers fell 53% from 1987, perhaps reflecting a weak year class resulting from the partial summer kill of adults in 1986 and 1988. White Sucker, Yellow Perch, and Sauger are slightly more abundant than in 1987. In 1988, Walleye numbers increased 21% from 1987 netting totals, and Walleye 16 inches or larger totaled 38% of the catch. This is above the 1987 and 1986 totals of 25% and 23% and 16.0 inches respectively. The mean from 1980-85 is 21.3 and the 1968-70 mean is 7.3% of the catch and 16.0 inches. The 1989 index netting will likely see a slight reduction in percentage of Walleye 16.0 inches, due to a strong 1987 year class and reflecting the reduced vulnerability to our sampling gear of these fish as they surpass 20 inches in total length.

The walleye population is in very good shape with about 15 age groups represented annually. The oldest walleye sampled in the 2001 fall gill net assessment was a 17 year-old male. The 1991 year class walleye are no longer a major component of the gill net sample. The majority of the 1991 year class walleye have outgrown the experimental gill net, and only about 10% of the supplementary large mesh gill net was of this strong year class. The 1991 walleye year class remains the strongest measured on Lake of the Woods. Since the weak year classes of 1992 and 1993, no weak year classes have been measured, though the 2000 year class is predicted to be very weak. The paucity of age-1 walleye in the gill net sample supports the prediction of a weak 2000 walleye year class. The walleye gill net CPUE was 50% higher than the 1992-2001 mean CPUE. Over 12% of the walleye sample was of the 2001 year class. It appears that the 2001 walleye year class will be quite strong, similar in strength to the 1991 year class.The sauger population has been characterized by highly variable recruitment. From 1991 through 1996 three weak year classes, but no strong year classes, were produced. The 1997 year class is the first strong year class since the 1989 and 1990 year classes. The 1989 and 1990 year classes are virtually gone from the sauger population. The 1993 and 1994 year-classes are of moderate strength. Sauger from these year-classes averaged between 14 and 16 inches long (depending on sex) in fall assessment netting, but comprised only 5% of the sauger sample. The two most abundant year classes were produced in1997 and 1999. The 1997 year class sauger average 12-13 inches in length and comprised 28% of the gill net sample. Nineteen ninety-nine year class sauger were just over 40% of the gill net sample and averaged about 9 inches in length. The 1999 year class was predicted to be of moderate strength, but based on this year gill net sample, it may be strong. Ice anglers readily accept sauger when they reach 11 inches in length. Over 45% of the fall gill net sauger sample exceeded 11 inches long. Sauger abundance has been increasing consistently since the low point in 1997, and overall abundance is at it's highest level in the past 10 years.Year class strength of walleye and sauger can be predicted with a fairly high degree of confidence based on information collected during YOY percid assessment, conducted during July and August. The variable used to predict walleye year class strength is the length that YOY walleye achieve by August 15. Length and year class strength are positively correlated. YOY walleye abundance has not been shown to be a significant effect to year class strength. Based on August 15 length, the 2001 walleye year class will be weak. However, the number of YOY walleye sampled in fall gill net assessment suggests that the 2001 year class will be quite strong. The number of YOY walleye sampled in fall gill net assessment is not a sensitive predictor of walleye year class strength, but strong year classes usually show up in this assessment series. Sauger year class strength can be predicted using YOY sauger abundance, measured through August trawling, and walleye abundance, measured through fall gill net assessment. Young of year sauger abundance is positively correlated with year class strength, while walleye abundance has an inverse relationship with sauger year class strength. YOY sauger abundance was moderate to low based on 2001 trawling while fall walleye gill net CPUE was high. The combination of these variables predict that the 2001 sauger year class will be weak.Northern pike are not sampled very effectively with standard lake assessment gill nets. In the 1983 to 1994 fall gill net assessment, northern pike CPUE has ranged from 0.8 to 2.7 with a 10 year mean of 1.5. The problem of small sample size has been addressed with a spring survey, using trap nets. Spring spawning run trap net assessment depicts a very high quality northern pike population. In 1995 the spawning run assessment was expanded to a tagging study, and 1,500 northern pike were tagged. The primary purpose of this study was to determine whether northern pike using streams in Minnesota as spawning sites were exclusively Minnesota stocks, or if the stocks were shared with the provinces of Manitoba and/or Ontario. In 1995, 15% of 1,432 tagged pike exceeded 750 mm (~30 inches). Approximately 2% of tagged northern pike exceed 1,000 mm (~40 inches). Preliminary tag return data suggest that the northern pike that spawn in Rainy River tributary streams spend their time in the Rainy River and are a distinct stock from the pike that spawn in Lake of the Woods tributaries. Rainy River tributary streams, as a group, have significantly smaller mean lengths than any of the other sites at which northern pike are tagged. Zippel Bay and the Warroad River stood out as sites from which a lot of tags were returned. These are areas that have a relatively high proportion of targeted northern pike effort. Based on tag returns, northern pike exploitation estimates range from 5.3-7% (depending on whether 30% or 40% of tags are reported) and survival is estimated at 66%. Data from the summer 2001 creel survey are available. This past summer was, once again, one of excellent walleye fishing success on Lake of the Woods. Despite that pressure was 6% lower than the five-year mean, harvest was 21% above the five year mean walleye harvest. The excellent fishing success was likely due to the very low abundance of age-1 yellow perch. Walleye angling success peaked from June 1-15 at 0.68 walleye per hour (0.47 harvested and 0.21 released). Combined (harvested and released) walleye angling CPUE did not drop below 0.40 until the August 16-31 time period. Overall summer walleye CPUE was 0.49 (0.35 harvested and 0.14 released). The summer harvest of walleye on the Minnesota waters of Lake of the Woods was 411,425 pounds, from a pressure of 745,983 angler hours.About 29,000 pounds of sauger were harvested during the summer of 2001. The overall non-targeted harvest rate of sauger was 0.05, with an overall non-targeted catch rate of 0.09. There were distinct catch rate differences between user groups. Non-guided parties had a total catch rate of about 0.07. Launch based anglers, which fish primarily with downriggers farther off shore than the non-guided anglers, had a total catch rate of 0.16, with a harvest rate of 0.09.

Two distinct modes in the length frequency distribution correspond to age-1 (2003 year class) and age-3 (2001 year class) walleye. The strength of these year classes has not been scored yet, but, year class strength of walleye can be predicted with a high degree of confidence (r2=0.89) based on information collected during YOY percid assessment, conducted during July and August. The variables used to predict walleye year class strength are the length that YOY walleye achieve by August 15 and the age-0 walleye CPUE from August trawling. Length, trawl CPUE and year class strength are positively correlated. The year class strength model suggests that the 2001 and 2003 walleye year classes are strong. The five-year mean total walleye harvest (all creel surveys combined) remains well above the target harvest at 636,650 pounds. In 2004 an intensive effort was undertaken to learn more about the lake sturgeon in Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system, and to estimate the population size. The entire project was a cooperative venture between the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources, the Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and the Rainy River First Nation. During the spring of 2004 the sturgeon were tagged. The cooperating agencies were able to capture and tag 811 sturgeon, using gill nets and bare hands. Anglers fishing in the area in which agency crews were tagging donated an additional 938 sturgeon to the cause, for a total of 1,749 tagged fish. During the summer recapture phase, 659 lake sturgeon were examined for tags. Eight fish tagged in 2004 were found.The largest sturgeon sampled during this program was 1,810 mm long and was caught and tagged by a volunteer angler. Generally, angler caught sturgeon were smaller than sturgeon sampled by agency personnel. Thirty one percent of the sturgeon sampled, longer than 1,000 mm (~40 inches), were in the harvest slot of 45-50 inches. The population estimate of sturgeon longer than 1,000 mm (~40 inches).was 74,143 (95% CI 39,719 - 151,657).

Lake of the Woods straddles the Canada-United States border, and is shared between the Canadian provinces of Manitoba and Ontario, and the U. S. state of Minnesota. Water level is directly controlled through three hydroelectric dams located at the head of the Winnipeg River in Kenora, Ontario. The Rainy River provides 75% of the inflow to the lake. Water flow into the Rainy River is controlled through a hydroelectric dam located between Fort Frances, Ontario and International Falls, Minnesota.

The lake is comprised of several distinct basins. The Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods (320,000 acres) lies within Muskeg Bay, Big Traverse Bay and Little Traverse Bay. Big Traverse Bay and Muskeg Bay are largely devoid of bottom structure and islands. Little Traverse Bay is more characteristic of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods, with numerous islands and reefs. These three basins do not stratify and in most years have widespread, dense, blue-green algae blooms that are first evident in July and continue through September.

The largest and most important lakes in Minnesota are sampled every year, in order to closely monitor their fish populations. Lake of the Woods is one of the ten lakes included in this Large Lake Sampling Program. These lakes are at least 15,000 acres in size, and typically support the best walleye fisheries in the state.

Anglers fish the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods for a variety of species, including walleye, sauger, yellow perch, northern pike and lake sturgeon. Due to the importance of walleye and sauger, a great deal of population monitoring effort is focused on them. Overviews of the sampling programs conducted on Lake of the Woods are located on the Baudette Area Fisheries web page, on the MN-DNR web site, at www.mndnr.gov/areas/fisheries/baudette.


Walleye

Walleye catches in the 2010 gill net sampling averaged 13.6 walleye per gill net. This level of abundance is slightly below the long-term average of 14.7 walleye per gill net. Walleye abundance declined steadily from 2001 through 2009, from 22.3 to 9.1 walleye per gill net. For perspective, abundance of the 2001 walleye sample was the highest measured since 1970.

Even though gill net catches have declined since 2001, the actual harvestable walleye population has not dropped to the same degree. In years when a strong year class is produced, a substantial portion of the walleye sample is comprised of very small (typically 5 to 8 inches long) walleye. In 2001, about 25% of the sample was these 5 to 8 inch long walleye. In 2010, the catch rate of walleye longer than 12 inches (the size anglers prefer to catch and keep) was actually higher than the catch rate of walleye 12 inches and longer in 2001.


Sauger

The sauger population is at a very high level of abundance. Sauger abundance has been increasing steadily over the past four years. The 1968 to 2009 average catch is 12.9 sauger per gill net. During fall gill netting in 2010, the sample had an impressive 25.5 sauger per net.

The increase in sauger abundance is due to the consistent production of strong year classes in recent years, and the presence of the very strong 2006 year class. This single year class comprises 60% of the sauger sample, and is the strongest sauger year class documented since 1982. Sauger from this year class averaged about 12 inches in length during fall gill net sampling.


Lake Sturgeon

Fishing for lake sturgeon is a unique opportunity in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. The lake sturgeon population is still recovering from a period of low abundance caused by over harvest and pollution. During the recovery phase we have to be conservative with the number and pounds of sturgeon harvested to ensure that the population fully recovers to a healthy size structure and level of abundance. In order to harvest a lake sturgeon, anglers must purchase a harvest tag. However no tag is required to fish catch-and-release for lake sturgeon. Anglers may harvest one lake sturgeon per year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. The lake sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for lake sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).


Infested Waters Designation

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of spiny water flea (Bythotrephes longimanus). Spiny water flea has been documented in Lake of the Woods, Rainy River and Rainy Lake. The impact of spiny water flea on the food chain and fish populations of Lake of the Woods is still open to speculation.

Zooplankton sampling has been initiated to document changes in the zooplankton community of Lake of the Woods. Two sites are sampled every other week from mid-June through August. Nine meter vertical tows are made with a 150 micron, 30 cm diameter plankton net.

At this date, the most immediate impact of spiny water flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. Local bait shops and resorts have had significant businesses harvesting bait within the system. There is concern that spiny water flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that spiny water flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-licensed individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

Rusty crayfish (Orconectes rusticus) were documented in the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods in September 2006. At this point rusty crayfish appear to be present in fairly low densities, and only as far south as Driftwood Point, just south-east of Garden Island. Rusty crayfish, a native of the Ohio River system, have been established in parts of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods since the late 1960s.

Walleye and Sauger

The primary assessment used to monitor walleye and sauger populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. The off-shore nets are analyzed separately from the standard nets due to differences in catch rate and size distribution.

Walleye. Walleye catches in the 2015 near-shore gill net sampling averaged 14.7 walleye per gill net, which just below the 1968-2014 average of 15.1. Walleye were more abundant in the off-shore portions of the lake in September of 2015, with 26.3 Walleye per gill net, which is well above the 2002 to 2014 average of 16.6. Overall Walleye abundance (16.9 per lift) was above the 2002 to 2014 average abundance of 16.2 Walleye per lift.

The number of walleye sampled annually can be quite variable due to the presence or absence of strong year classes in the population, and environmental conditions that affect netting efficiency. Walleye abundance declined steadily from 2001 through 2009, from 22.3 to 9.1 walleye per gill net. This decline in abundance was attributable to the unusually abundant walleye population in 2001, due to the production of a series of strong year classes in the late 1990s and in 2001, which pushed overall abundance well above the long-term average of 15.1 walleye per gill net. More recently, the 2011 year class is strong, and early indications are that the 2013 year class will be moderately strong
The most abundant size groups of walleye are from 7 to 10 inches long (2014 and 2015 year classes), and from 14-16 inches long (primarily from the 2011 year class).

Sauger. The highest sauger abundance measured in the fall gill net assessment was in 2009, when we found 30.8 sauger per lift. This high abundance was driven by young sauger from the strong year classes produced from 2005 through 2007, and there were relatively few keepers available. As these sauger have grown older, overall abundance has declined, but a high quality size structure has developed. Overall sauger abundance declined from 2009 through 2013, because only the 2011 year class was strong through this period. From 2002 through 2014 Sauger tended to be much more abundant in the off-shore sample than in the near-shore sample. In 2015 they were almost equally distributed at 16.6 Sauger per lift in the near-shore sites, and 15.7 in the off-shore sites. This compares to 2002 to 2014 averages of 16.1 and 24.7, respectively. Overall, Sauger abundance was 16.4 Sauger per lift, down from the 2002 to 2014 average of 19.5 per lift.
Sauger from 11 to 13 inches long are all more abundant than the long-term average, and sauger from 13 to 16 inches long are well represented in the sauger population.

Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality northern pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" northern pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the northern pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites. The northern pike population continues to be one of high quality, with 19% of the adult population at least 35 inches long, and 5% of the adults 40 inches long, or longer. The next northern pike sample is scheduled to be collected in the spring of 2015, though the low runoff we are experiencing may prevent that sampling program from being completed.

Lake Sturgeon

The third population estimate for lake sturgeon since 1990 was completed in 2014. Previous estimates for lake sturgeon (40-inches and longer) were 16,000 (1990) and 59,000 (2004). In 2014 we estimate that there were 92,000 lake sturgeon of 40-inches and longer in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. Along with the increase in abundance, we also found that the number of "large" sturgeon increased. The largest sturgeon we sampled was 72-inches long, and had an estimated weight of 104 pounds.

Fisheries Management

In December of 2017, DNR Fisheries in Baudette began a management plan review/revision for Lake of the Woods, and solicited input from the public and a Fisheries Input Group. Stated within the fisheries management plan is a brief background of management history, series of management goals and objectives and management actions. The plan is effective for five years and goals/objectives will be reevaluated in 2023. The final plan can be found at: https://files.dnr.state.mn.us/fisheries/largelakes/low/low_plan.pdf

Walleye

Since 2002, the average Walleye catch rate or catch per unit effort (CPUE) is 16.2 fish/net (both near and off-shore nets combined). The 2022 CPUE was 12.8 fish/net and up from 2021 (11.5 fish/net). The current 3-year average for CPUE is 12.4 fish/net and fell below the 2018-2023 management goal ~ 14 fish/net. Gill net sampled Walleye ranged in length from 3.4 to 31.1 inches with an average length of 12.6 inches. Small Walleye (~ 8-10 inches) were above average, while keeper-sized Walleye (14 to 19 inches) were below the historic average. Walleye 11 to 14 inches were well below historic levels, the result of weaker year-classes being produced in 2019 and 2020. Lastly, gill net catch rate for large Walleye (> 20 inches) was 1.3 fish/net in 2022 with a stable trend the past decade (1 to 2.2 fish per net).

Sauger

In 2022, Sauger gill net CPUE was 16.2 fish/net and the current 3-year average (21.5 fish/net) exceeds the 2018-2023 management goal of ~ 16 fish/net. Above average Sauger abundance experienced the past few years is the result of several strong year-classes being produced over the past decade. However, low gill net and trawl catches of small Sauger (> 10 inches) in 2022 suggests weaker than average year-classes for 2020 and 2021. Sauger sampled in 2022, ranged in length from 3 to 17.2 inches with an average length of 11.4 inches. Sauger greater than 11 inches were well above average.

Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality Northern Pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" Northern Pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the Northern Pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites. Trap netting conducted in 2022 revealed a high-quality size structure for sampled tributaries to Lake of the Woods. Fall gill netting in 2022 sampled Northern Pike from 8.5 to 41.9 inches with an average length of 23.3 inches.

Yellow Perch

Yellow Perch are often not targeted by anglers fishing Lake of the Woods, but are caught incidentally fishing for Walleye and Sauger. Under the current fisheries management plan for 2018-2023 no population level goals are set for Yellow Perch, but they are of management interest. Results from 2022 indicate perch near-shore abundance was above the 10-year average and was the highest observed since 2003. Catch rates for Yellow Perch are highly variable, but have slightly declined since the early 1990s. Yellow Perch ranged in length from 4.8 to 13.6 inches with an average length of 7.9 inches.

Lake Sturgeon

Since 2004, spawning Lake Sturgeon are sampled annually on the Rapid River (a tributary to the Rainy River). Over the past 15 years there has been an overall increase in mean length and greater proportion of "large" sturgeon in the sampled population. In addition to obtaining lengths, sampled Lake Sturgeon are tagged with a unique number at the base of the dorsal fin. This information has revealed that males typically spawn every 2 to 3 years (in some cases annually) and females spawn every 4 to 9 years. In total over 2,000 fish have been tagged at the Rapid River and over 10,000 have been tagged system-wide since the inception of the tagging program. In addition to natural resource sampling, nearly 250 tag returns are reported annually by anglers. This information provides information on movement patterns, spawning occurrence, growth, and harvest metrics.

In order to harvest a Lake Sturgeon, anglers must purchase a harvest tag. However no tag is required to fish catch-and-release for Lake Sturgeon. Anglers may harvest one Lake Sturgeon per calendar year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest; harvested sturgeon must be registered per guidance in regulation book. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. The Lake Sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for Lake Sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).

Infested Waters Designation

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of Spiny Water Flea and Zebra Mussel. Spiny Water Flea was first documented in the late 2000s in the Minnesota waters of Lake of the Woods. Zebra Mussel veligers (lavae) were first sampled by fisheries staff in Muskeg Bay in 2019. No adult Zebra Mussel were observed in 2022.

At this date, the most immediate impact of Spiny Water Flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald Shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. Local bait shops and resorts have had significant businesses harvesting bait within the system. There is concern that Spiny Water Flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that Spiny Water Flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-permitted individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

The walleye population is in very good shape with about 15 age groups represented annually. The oldest walleye sampled in the 2002 fall gill net assessment was a 18 year-old, 689 mm long female. The 1991 year class walleye are no longer a major component of the gill net sample. The majority of the 1991 year class walleye have outgrown the experimental gill net, and just over 13% of the supplementary large mesh gill net was of this strong year class. The 1991 walleye year class had been the strongest measured on Lake of the Woods (since 1984), but the 1999 year class appears to be of similar strength. Year class strength of walleye and sauger can be predicted with a fairly high degree of confidence (r2=0.74) based on information collected during YOY percid assessment, conducted during July and August. The variables used to predict walleye year class strength are the length that YOY walleye achieve by August 15 and the age-0 walleye CPUE from August trawling. Length, CPUE and year class strength are positively correlated. The length YOY walleye achieved by August 15 length and their trawl CPUE suggest that the 2001 walleye year class will be very strong, but that the 2002 year class will be weak.Overall the walleye population is in very good shape. Abundance (21.4 walleye per lift), measured in fall gill net assessment, was similar to 2001 and remained above the 10-year mean abundance of 14.8. Walleye catches in the 2008 gill net sampling averaged 10.3 walleye per gill net. This level of abundance is well below the long-term average of 14.9 walleye per gill net. Walleye abundance has declined steadily since 2001, when 22.3 walleye per gill net were sampled. Abundance of the 2001 walleye sample was the highest measured since 1970.

The high abundance in 2001 was the result of a series of moderate and strong year classes produced from 1994 through 2001. During that eight-year span, only one weak year class was produced, in 2000. Strong back-to-back year classes are unusual in a walleye population. From 2000 through 2008, four weak, four moderate, and only one strong (2001) year class have been produced. Significant variation in abundance is normal for walleye, and all members of the perch family.

Even though gill net catches have declined substantially since 2001, the actual harvestable walleye population has not dropped to the same degree. In years when a strong year class is produced, a substantial portion of the walleye sample is comprised of very small (typically 5 to 8 inches long) walleye. In 2001, about 25% of the sample was these 5 to 8 inch long walleye. In 2008, the portion of the sample, that is of a size anglers prefer to catch and keep, is still almost 70% of the same portion of the population in 2001.

So, how will this abundance decline influence angling success? The short answer is likely very little. Overall fish abundance does play a role in angler success, but other factors, such as weather patterns and forage abundance, are frequently a much greater influence. As an extreme example, very poor fishing was experienced during the winter of 2005-06. The primary influence during that winter was a series of wind storms that occurred just as the ice was forming on the lake. The wind storms caused the water to become very muddy, and the suspended sediments did not settle out until very late in the winter.

Anglers can expect to catch a wide range of walleye sizes this winter. Walleye from 12 through 18 inches were all well represented in the gill net sample.

In contrast to the walleye population, the sauger population is at its highest level of abundance measured since fall gill net sampling started in 1968. Sauger abundance has been increasing steadily over the past four years. The 1968 to 2008 average catch is 12.3 sauger per gill net. During fall gill netting in 2008, the sample had an impressive 26.0 sauger per net. Just as the walleye gill net catch rate should not be interpreted as gloomy, the sauger catch rate also has to be taken in context. Only about 30% of the sample exceeded 12 inches in length, with sauger between 9 and 10 inches long comprising another 30% of the sample.

The increase in sauger abundance is due to the consistent production of good year classes in recent years, and the presence of the very strong 2006 year class. This single year class comprises almost 70% of the sauger sample, and is the strongest sauger year class documented since 1982. Most of the sauger from this year class will range from 8 to 10 inches in length, during the winter 2008-09 winter fishery.

Anglers can anticipate catching good numbers of 11-inch sauger, from the moderately strong 2005 year class. The very abundant 2006 year class sauger will be of "bait-stealer" size this winter, and anglers can expect to go through a lot of bait when the fishing is good.

Walleye and Sauger

The primary assessment used to monitor Walleye and Sauger populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. There are differences in the size structure and abundance of Walleye and Sauger in the near-shore and off-shore samples. Though the samples are combined in the data portion of this report, they are discussed separately in this narrative.

Walleye. Walleye catches in the 2016 near-shore gill net sample averaged 25.2 Walleye per gill net, which just well above the 1968-2015 average of 15.1. Walleye were also abundant in the off-shore portions of the lake, with 21.1 Walleye per gill net, which is well above the 2002 to 2015 average of 16.6. When the near-shore and off-shore samples are combined, it appears that Walleye are slightly more abundant than they were last year. The 2013 and 2014 year classes are both strong, and the 2015 and 2016 year classes are predicted to be of average strength. When this is combined with only a single weak year class (2008) in the past 10 years, the result is an abundant Walleye population.

Small Walleye, from 7 to 12 inches long, are currently quite abundant. "Keeper-size" Walleye are also abundant, with individuals from 13 to 18 inches being well represented.

Sauger. The highest Sauger abundance measured in the fall gill net assessment was in 2009, when we found 30.8 Sauger per lift. This high abundance was driven by young Sauger from the strong year classes produced from 2005 through 2007, and there were relatively few keepers available. As these Sauger have grown older, overall abundance has declined, but a high quality size structure has developed.

Overall abundance increased to the highest level since 2011, though this is being driven by a strong 2014 year class. These Sauger won't be large enough for most anglers to consider them to be keepers until the winter of 2018-19. Additionally, individuals from 7 to 10 inches long were also common. These small Sauger predict a good future for our Sauger population. Of interest to anglers is that Sauger from 12 to 15 inches were relatively abundant, and individuals to 18 inches long were sampled.
Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality Northern Pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" Northern Pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the Northern Pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites.

Two spawning sites were sampled in the spring of 2016. Due to weather issues, we were not able to sample a third site that was on the schedule. This site will be sampled in the spring of 2017.

Samples collected in the spring of 2016 show that the percentage of Northern Pike longer than 40 inches has remained stable at 6 to 8% of the females that were sampled, but the percentage of mid-size Northern Pike has declined a bit. Percentages are strongly influenced by the production of strong year classes, so the sample collected in 2017 should shed some light on if the decline is real or if there was simply a strong year class produced that diluted the percentage of the mid-sized fish.

Lake Sturgeon

The third population estimate for Lake Sturgeon since 1990 was completed in 2014. Previous estimates for Lake Sturgeon (40-inches and longer) were 16,000 (1990) and 59,000 (2004). In 2014 we estimate that there were 92,000 Lake Sturgeon of 40-inches and longer in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. Along with the increase in abundance, we also found that the number of "large" sturgeon increased. The largest sturgeon we sampled was 72-inches long, and had an estimated weight of 104 pounds.
Fishing for Lake Sturgeon is a unique opportunity in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. The Lake Sturgeon population is still recovering from a period of low abundance caused by over harvest and pollution. During the recovery phase we have to be conservative with the number and pounds of sturgeon harvested to ensure that the population fully recovers to a healthy size structure and level of abundance. Physical Description

Lake of the Woods straddles the Canada-United States border and is shared between the Canadian provinces of Manitoba and Ontario, and the U. S. state of Minnesota. Water level is directly controlled through three hydroelectric dams located at the head of the Winnipeg River in Kenora, Ontario. The Rainy River provides 75% of the inflow to the lake.

The lake is comprised of several distinct basins. The Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods (just over 300,000 acres) lies within Muskeg Bay, Big Traverse Bay and Little Traverse Bay. Big Traverse Bay and Muskeg Bay are largely devoid of bottom structure and islands. Little Traverse Bay is more characteristic of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods, with numerous islands and reefs. These three basins do not stratify and in most years have widespread, dense, blue-green algae blooms that are first evident in July and continue through October.

A fish population, such as Lake of the Woods walleye, with a variety of age classes present is a healthy fish population. Walleye from age-0 through age-18 were sampled in 2012. Of the six age-18 walleye sampled, two were males, with an average length of 23 inches, and four were female, with an average length of 28.4 inches. The largest walleye sampled was 30.0 inches long, and a relatively young 16 years old. A high proportion of the walleye sample (47%) was of age-1 individuals. Past experience suggests that a catch rate of age-1 individuals in this range predicts a strong year class.

Long-term mean abundance (1968-2012) is 14.8 walleye per gill net lift. The 2012 abundance was 18.9 per lift, above the long-term mean, but within the range of normal abundances.

Year class strength is indexed on the catch rates of a year class from age-2 through age-5, from fall gill net assessment. Year class strength is correlated to the abundance of age-0 walleye, as measured in Young-of-Year assessment trawling, and the length that age-0 walleye achieve by August 15 of the hatch year, so the strength of year classes can be predicted. Based on data collected during the summers of 2011 and 2012, the 2011 and 2012 walleye year classes are both expected to be strong, and of moderate strength, respectively.

Sauger

Sauger abundance is currently high, but is coming down from the very high abundance measured in 2009. Abundance has declined due to the passing through of the very strong series of year classes produced from 2005 through 2007. Of particular note is the 2006 year class. The 2006 year class is the strongest sauger year class measured since fall gill net assessment became an annual survey in 1981. Sauger from the 2006 year class comprised about 31% of the entire sauger sample, and had an average length of 14.5 inches.

Sauger year class strength can also be predicted from data collected during YOY percid assessment. In the case of sauger, year class strength is related to the abundance of age-0 sauger, as measured through August trawling. Based on data collected during the summers of 2011 and 2012, the 2011 and 2012 sauger year classes are predicted to be of moderate and weak strength, respectively.

Northern Pike

Northern pike are not sampled very effectively with standard lake assessment gill nets. From the 1968 to 2009 fall gill net assessments, northern pike CPUE ranged from 0.8 to 2.7 with a 10-year mean of 1.6. The problem of small sample size has been addressed with a spring survey, using trap nets. Spring spawning run trap net assessment depicts a very high quality northern pike population.

In 1995 the spawning run assessment was expanded to a tagging study, and 1,500 northern pike were to be tagged. The primary purpose of this study was to determine whether northern pike using streams in Minnesota as spawning sites were exclusively Minnesota stocks, or if the stocks were shared with the provinces of Manitoba and/or Ontario. In 1995, 15% of 1,432 tagged pike exceeded 30 inches. Approximately 2% of tagged northern pike exceeded 40 inches. Tag return data suggest that the northern pike that spawn in Rainy River tributary streams spend their time in the Rainy River and are a distinct stock from the pike that spawn in Lake of the Woods tributaries. Rainy River tributary streams, as a group, have significantly smaller mean lengths than any of the other sites at which northern pike were tagged. Zippel Bay and the Warroad River stood out as sites from which a high proportion of tags were returned. These are areas that have relatively high targeted northern pike angling effort. Based on tag returns, northern pike exploitation estimates range from 5.3-7% (depending on whether 30% or 40% of tags are reported) and survival is estimated at 66%.

Overall, 19% of the 716 northern pike sampled in 2011 exceeded 35 inches, and 5% exceeded 40 inches. Spring northern pike assessment is currently scheduled to take place on a five-year rotation. It was anticipated that all sites would be sampled in a single year, but this was not possible in 2011. The sites which could not be sampled were scheduled to be sampled in 2012. Unfortunately, with the lack of runoff, and the unusually early spring, it was decided to forego sampling northern pike in 2012 because it was likely that the data collected would not be comparable to other years.

Infested Waters Designation

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of spiny water flea (Bythotrephes longimanus). Spiny water flea has been documented in Lake of the Woods, Rainy River and Rainy Lake. The impact of spiny water flea on the food chain and fish populations of Lake of the Woods is still open to speculation. Zooplankton sampling has been initiated to document changes in the zooplankton community of Lake of the Woods. Two sites are sampled every other week from mid-June through August. Nine meter vertical tows are made with a 150 micron, 30 cm diameter plankton net.

At this point, the most immediate impact of spiny water flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. Local bait shops and resorts have had significant businesses harvesting bait within the system. There is concern that spiny water flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that spiny water flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-licensed individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

Rusty crayfish (Orconectes rusticus), a crayfish native to the Ohio River system, were documented in the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods in September 2006. At this point rusty crayfish appear to be present in fairly low densities, and only as far south as Driftwood Point, just south-west of Garden Island. Rusty crayfish have been established in parts of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods since the late 1960s.

Regulations

Current walleye and sauger harvest regulations were enacted on December 1, 2004. The regulations were enacted to reduce the five-year average walleye and sauger harvest to the target harvest of 450,000 pounds for walleye and 250,000 pounds for sauger. The regulations vary by time of year, location on the lake, and between Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River.

Lake of the Woods, from December 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is eight (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Lake of the Woods, from walleye opener through November 30, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is six (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Four Mile Bay of Lake of the Woods, from March 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is two (no walleye over 19.5 inches).

Rainy River from walleye opener through February, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is six (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Rainy River from March 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is two (no walleye over 19.5 inches).

To protect the high quality size structure of the northern pike population, a special northern pike regulation package was adopted with the opening of the fishing season in 2006. The regulation protects northern pike from 30 through 40 inches. Possession is 3 northern pike, of which only one can exceed 40 inches. The open season is continuous. This regulation went through a 10-year (1996 through 2005) experimental evaluation period prior to being adopted as a special regulation.

Fishing for lake sturgeon is a unique opportunity in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. The lake sturgeon population is still recovering from a period of low abundance caused by over harvest and pollution. During the recovery phase we have to be conservative with the number and pounds of sturgeon harvested to ensure that the population fully recovers to a healthy size structure and level of abundance. Anglers may harvest one lake sturgeon per year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. The lake sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for lake sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).

Starting in 2006, anglers wishing to harvest a lake sturgeon have had to purchase a lake sturgeon harvest tag. The tag is available through the electronic licensing system (any license issuing agent) and costs $5.00. Upon harvesting a sturgeon, the harvesting angler must notch the appropriate areas of the tag indicating the date and time of harvest, then the tag must be attached to the sturgeon. Within 48 hours a registration card must be completed by the harvesting angler and mailed in. Anglers do not need a harvest tag to catch and release lake sturgeon, a harvest tag is needed only if they intend to harvest one.

Anglers fish the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods for a variety of species, including Walleye, Sauger, Yellow Perch, Northern Pike and Lake Sturgeon. Due to the importance of Walleye and Sauger, a great deal of population monitoring effort is focused on them. Overviews of the sampling programs conducted on Lake of the Woods are located on the Baudette Area Fisheries web page, on the MN-DNR web site, at www.mndnr.gov/areas/fisheries/baudette.

Walleye and Sauger

The primary assessment used to monitor Walleye and Sauger populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. There are differences in the size structure and abundance of Walleye and Sauger in the near-shore and off-shore samples. Though the samples are combined in the data portion of this report, they are discussed separately in this narrative.

Walleye. Walleye catches in the 2017 near-shore gill net sample averaged 18.3 Walleye per gill net, which just well above the 1968-2016 average of 15.4. Walleye were also abundant in the off-shore portions of the lake, with 17.6 Walleye per gill net, which is well above the 2002 to 2016 average of 16.9. When the near-shore and off-shore samples are combined, Walleye are less abundant than they were last year. The 2013 and 2014 year classes are both strong, and the 2016 and 2017 year classes are predicted to be of average strength. When this is combined with only a single weak year class (2008) in the past 10 years, the result is an abundant Walleye population.

Small Walleye, from 7 to 12 inches long, are abundant. Harvestable-sized Walleye are also abundant, with individuals from 13 to 18 inches being well represented.

Sauger. The highest Sauger abundance measured in the fall gill net assessment was in 2009, when we found 30.8 Sauger per lift. This high abundance was driven by young Sauger from the strong year classes produced from 2005 through 2007, and there were relatively few keepers available. As these Sauger have grown older, overall abundance has declined, but a high quality size structure has developed.

Overall abundance increased to the highest level since 2011, driven by strong 2014 and 2015 year classes. These Sauger won't be large enough for most anglers to consider them to be keepers until the winter of 2018-19. Additionally, individuals from 7 to 10 inches long were also common. These small Sauger predict a good future for the Sauger population. Of interest to anglers is that Sauger from 12 to 15 inches were relatively abundant, and individuals to 18 inches long were sampled.

Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality Northern Pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" Northern Pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the Northern Pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites.

Two spawning sites were sampled in the spring of 2017. Samples collected in the spring of 2017 show that the percentage of Northern Pike longer than 40 inches has remained stable at 8 to 13% of the females that were sampled. Mid-sized Northern Pike are categorized as fish 30 to 40 inches. Percentage of mid-sized Northern Pike at both sites sampled in 2017 also have remained stable since the mid-2000s.

Lake Sturgeon

The third population estimate for Lake Sturgeon since 1990 was completed in 2014. Previous estimates for Lake Sturgeon (40-inches and longer) were 16,000 (1990) and 59,000 (2004). In 2014 we estimate that there were 92,000 Lake Sturgeon of 40-inches and longer in the Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system. Along with the increase in abundance, we also found that the number of "large" sturgeon increased. The largest sturgeon we sampled was 72-inches long, and had an estimated weight of 104 pounds.

Physical Description

Lake of the Woods straddles the Canada-United States border, and is shared between the Canadian provinces of Manitoba and Ontario, and the U. S. state of Minnesota. Water level is directly controlled through three hydroelectric dams located at the head of the Winnipeg River in Kenora, Ontario. The Rainy River provides 75% of the inflow to the lake.

Little Traverse Bay is more characteristic of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods, with numerous islands and reefs. These three basins do not stratify and in most years have widespread, dense, blue-green algae blooms that are first evident in July and continue through October.

The largest and most important lakes in Minnesota are sampled every year, in order to closely monitor their fish populations. The primary assessment used to monitor fish populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. There are differences in the size structure and abundance of fish species in the near-shore and off-shore samples.

Walleye

Since 2002 the average Walleye catch rate or catch per unit effort (CPUE) is 16.8 fish/net (both near and off-shore nets combined). The 2018 CPUE was 15.3 fish/net and down from 2017 (18.2 fish/net), but exceeded the 2018-2023 management goal ~ 14 fish/net. Gill net sampled Walleye ranged in length from 5.2 to 30.5 inches with an average length of 13.2 inches. Several small Walleye (7 to 8 inches) were sampled during the fall gill net assessment; that coupled with above average growth and abundance is an indication of a strong year-class produced in 2018. In addition, keeper-sized Walleye were at or exceeded historic levels. Walleye 9 to 11 inches were below historic levels and is the result of the 2016 and 2017 year-classes being of moderate strength. Lastly, the 2018-2023 fisheries management plan calls for the annual percentage of gill net sampled Walleye over 20 inches to be 5 to 15% of the total catch. In 2018, just over 10% the Walleye sampled were 20 inches or larger.

Sauger

In 2018 Sauger gill net CPUE was 26 fish/net and exceeds the 2018-2023 management goal of ~ 16 fish/net. Above average Sauger abundance experienced the past few years is the result of strong year-classes being produced in 2011 and from 2014-2016. Year-classes produced in 2017 and 2018 are predicted to be moderate to weak. Sauger sampled in 2018 ranged in length from 6.5 to 19.25 inches with an average length of 11.5 inches. Sauger from 7 to 17 inches are at or exceed historic levels.

Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality Northern Pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" Northern Pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the Northern Pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites. Trap netting conducted in 2016 and 2017 revealed a high-quality size structure for all sampled tributaries to Lake of the Woods and Rainy River. Fall gill netting in 2018 sampled Northern Pike from 17.5 to 44 inches with an average length of 28 inches.

Yellow Perch

Yellow Perch are often not targeted by anglers fishing Lake of the Woods, but caught incidentally fishing for Walleye and Sauger. Under the current fisheries management plan for 2018-2023 no population level goals are set for Yellow Perch but are of management interest. Results from 2018 indicate perch near-shore abundance is above the 10-year average marking the third year in row. Perch ranged in length from 5 to nearly 14 inches with an average length of 9 inches and likely from the 2015 year-class.

Lake Sturgeon

Since 2004 spawning Lake Sturgeon are sampled annually on the Rapid River (a tributary to the Rainy River). Over the past 14 years there has been an overall increase in mean length and greater proportion of "large" sturgeon in the sampled population. In addition to obtaining lengths, sampled Lake Sturgeon were tagged with a unique number at the base of the dorsal fin. This information has revealed that males typically spawn every 2 to 3 years (in some cases annually) and females spawn every 4 to 9 years. In total nearly 2,000 fish have been tagged at the Rapid River and over 9,000 have been tagged system-wide since the inception of the tagging program. In addition to natural resource sampling, nearly 200 tag returns are reported annually by anglers. This information provides information on movement patterns, spawning occurrence, growth, and harvest metrics.

In order to harvest a Lake Sturgeon, anglers must purchase a harvest tag. However no tag is required to fish catch-and-release for Lake Sturgeon. Anglers may harvest one Lake Sturgeon per calender year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. The Lake Sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for Lake Sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).

Infested Waters Designation

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of Spiny Water Flea. Spiny Water Flea has been documented in Lake of the Woods, Rainy River and Rainy Lake. The impact of Spiny Water Flea on the food chain and fish populations of Lake of the Woods is still open to speculation, but being monitored closely.

At this date, the most immediate impact of Spiny Water Flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. Local bait shops and resorts have had significant businesses harvesting bait within the system. There is concern that Spiny Water Flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that Spiny Water Flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-permitted individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

Rusty Crayfish have displaced the native crayfish within 2 years of colonizing an area, and have been associated with declines in aquatic vegetation when they become established.

The walleye population is in good shape, with at least 15 age classes represented annually. A fish population, such as Lake of the Woods walleye, with a variety of age classes present is a healthy fish population. Walleye from age-0 through age-20 were sampled in 2011. The longest individual sampled was a 28.0 inch long. A relatively high proportion of the walleye sample (16%) was of age-0 individuals. Past experience suggests that a catch rate of age-0 individuals in this range predicts a moderately strong to strong year class. Long-term mean abundance (1968-2011) is 14.8 walleye per gill net lift. The 2011 abundance was 19.7 per lift, above the long-term mean, but within the range of normal abundances.

Sauger abundance is currently very high. Sauger abundance is 21.0 sauger per gill net, and is down from the record high of 30.8, measured in 2009. Mean abundance, from 1968-2011, is 13.5 sauger per gill net. The high sauger abundance can be attributed to the production of three strong year classes (2005, 2006 and 2007), combined with only two weak year classes, in the past ten years. Of particular note is the 2006 year class. The 2006 year class is the strongest sauger year class measured since fall gill net assessment became an annual survey in 1981. The yellow perch population is at an average level of abundance, after being well below average since 2007. The increase in abundance is being driven by a high proportion of age-1 individuals, suggesting that the 2010 yellow perch year class is strong. Lake of the Woods Regulations

Current walleye and sauger harvest regulations were enacted on December 1, 2004. The regulations vary by time of year, location on the lake, and between Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River.

Lake of the Woods, from December 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is eight (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Lake of the Woods, from walleye opener through November 30, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is six (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Four Mile Bay of Lake of the Woods, from March 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is two (no walleye over 19.5 inches).

Rainy River from walleye opener through February, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is six (not more than four can be walleye). Walleye from 19.5 to 28 inches must be immediately released. Only one walleye over 28 inches total length can be possessed.

Rainy River from March 1 through April 14, the walleye/sauger aggregate limit is two (no walleye over 19.5 inches).

The northern pike possession limit is 3, of which only one can exceed 40 inches. The open season is continuous.

The lake sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. Anglers may harvest one lake sturgeon per year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. Anglers wishing to harvest a lake sturgeon must purchase a lake sturgeon harvest tag. The tag is available through the electronic licensing system (any license issuing agent) and costs $5.00. Upon harvesting a sturgeon, the harvesting angler must notch the appropriate areas of the tag indicating the date and time of harvest, then the tag must be attached to the sturgeon. Within 48 hours a registration card must be completed by the harvesting angler and mailed in.

Anglers do not need a harvest tag to catch and release lake sturgeon, a harvest tag is needed only if they intend to harvest one. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for lake sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).

The primary assessment used to monitor walleye and sauger populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. The off-shore nets are analyzed separately from the standard nets due to differences in catch rate and size distribution.

Walleye. Walleye catches in the 2014 near-shore gill net sampling averaged about 23 walleye per gill net, which is well above the long-term average of 14.7. The number of walleye sampled annually can be quite variable due to the presence or absence of strong year classes in the population. Walleye abundance declined steadily from 2001 through 2009, from 22.3 to 9.1 walleye per gill net. This decline in abundance was attributable to the unusually abundant walleye population in 2001, due to the production of a series of strong year classes in the late 1990s and in 2001, which pushed overall abundance well above the long-term average of 14.7 walleye per gill net. After 2001 moderate year classes alternated with weak year classes, causing an overall decline in abundance. More recently, the 2011 year class is strong, and early indications are that the 2013 year class will be strong. As these year classes continue to recruit to the walleye sample overall abundance will remain high, or increase.

The most abundant size groups of walleye are from 8 to 10 inches long (2013 year class), and from 12 to 14 inches long (2011 year class).

Sauger. The highest sauger abundance measured in the fall gill net assessment was in 2009, when we found 30.8 sauger per lift. This high abundance was driven by young sauger from the strong year classes produced from 2005 through 2007, and there were relatively few keepers available. As these sauger have grown older, overall abundance has declined, but a high quality size structure has developed. Overall sauger abundance declined from 2009 through 2013, because only the 2011 year class was strong through this period. Sauger from the 2011 year class were too small to be effectively captured in the gill nets, until 2014. Sauger abundance jumped up in 2014 due to the recruitment of the 2011 year class to the sample.

Sauger from 9 to 13 inches long are all more abundant than the long-term average.

The northern pike population continues to be one of high quality, with 19% of the adult population at least 35 inches long, and 5% of the adults 40 inches long, or longer. Lake Sturgeon

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of spiny water flea (Bythotrephes longimanus). At this date, the most immediate impact of spiny water flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. There is concern that spiny water flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that spiny water flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-licensed individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

Since 1997, odd numbered years have produced strong year classes while even numbered years have produced only moderate or weak year classes. For the spring and summer of 2007, anglers will notice an abundance of four and six year old walleye. The four year old walleye will grow from about 12 to 14 inches in length through the summer, while the six year olds range from 14 to 16 inches long. Two year old walleye, from the strong 2005 year class, are very abundant, but their 9-10 inch average length puts them in the "bait stealer" category. Sauger

Fall gill net sampling indicates that sauger are more abundant than their 10-year average abundance. In the past 10 years, sauger were most abundant in 2002. Sauger abundance declined rapidly through 2004, but has increased since then. Sauger abundance should continue to increase as good year classes recruit to the fishery. Summer sampling suggests that the sauger year class produced in 2006 will be very strong.

More than 60 percent of the fall gill net sauger sample exceeded 11 inches in length. High-quality sauger, those longer than 14 inches, comprised 25 percent of the sample. Along with these "keepers," 20 percent of the sample ranged in length from 7 to 9 inches. The majority of these sauger are one year old. Sauger rarely exceed 15 years old.

Northern Pike

The northern pike regulation on Lake of the Woods, Rainy River and several tributary streams is designed to protect the size structure of the pike population. An experimental regulation was evaluated from 1996 through 2005. After 10 years with the experimental regulation, a 2005 evaluation of the northern pike population indicated the number of pike over 36 inches increased from seven percent of the sample to 16 percent. The percentage of northern pike longer than 40 inches increased from two to four percent. The largest northern pike in the population are typically 12 to 15 years old. Based on this improvement, the regulation was made permanent in 2006.


Special Regulations

Anglers should be aware of special fishing regulations on Lake of the Woods. These regulations are designed to maintain a quality fishery and fishing experience. The combined walleye-sauger limit is six, but no more than four of those fish may be walleye. All walleye between 19.5 and 28 inches in length must be immediately released, and only one walleye longer than 28 inches may be possessed.

Northern pike are also managed by special regulation. The possession limit is three. All northern pike between 30-40 inches must be released immediately. An angler may possess one northern pike over 40 inches.

The Lake of the Woods-Rainy River system is one of the very few water systems that has a sturgeon population that is healthy enough to support a sport fishery which has a harvest component. Due to sturgeon life history, they are highly prone to over-harvest. To protect the sturgeon population, yet still allow some harvest, the sturgeon fishery is tightly controlled. Anglers wishing to harvest a sturgeon must purchase a sturgeon harvest tag. The tag must be validated and submitted when a sturgeon has been harvested. No harvest tag is required to catch-and-release fish for sturgeon. Sturgeon fishing also has a closed season (no fishing for sturgeon is allowed), catch-and-release season (fishing is allowed, but none may be harvested) and a harvest season. Check the Minnesota-Ontario border waters section of the fishing regulations for specific season dates.

Spiny water flea was discovered in Rainy Lake last summer, and it is anticipated that Lake of the Woods will be colonized during the summer of 2007. As a precaution, Lake of the Woods has been designated as infested with spiny water flea. With the infestation, anglers have some obligations to prevent the spread of this invader to other water bodies. Anglers must make sure they do not transport any lake water in their boats. Bilges, live wells and bait wells must all be drained at boat landings. Also, spiny water flea tends to wrap around fishing line, so anglers must clean their fishing equipment when leaving the lake. Check the DNR web site for more specific information of how to prevent the spread of spiny water flea.

The largest and most important lakes in Minnesota are sampled every year, in order to closely monitor their fish populations. Lake of the Woods is one of the large lakes included in this Large Lake Sampling Program. These lakes are at least 15,000 acres in size, and typically support the best Walleye fisheries in the state. Anglers fish the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods for a variety of species, including Walleye, Sauger, Yellow Perch, Northern Pike and Lake Sturgeon. Due to the importance of Walleye and Sauger, a great deal of population monitoring effort is focused on them. Overviews of the sampling programs conducted on Lake of the Woods are located on the Baudette Area Fisheries web page, on the MN-DNR web site, at www.mndnr.gov/areas/fisheries/baudette.

The primary assessment used to monitor fish populations is fall gill net assessment. This assessment has been annual since 1981, but a comparable assessment was conducted from 1968 through 1970. From 1968 through 2001, the fall gill net assessment sampled the near-shore waters of Lake of the Woods, from 6 to 25 feet in depth. In 2002 off-shore nets were added to the assessment. The off-shore nets sample water from 32 to 35 feet deep. There are differences in the size structure and abundance of fish species in the near-shore and off-shore samples.

Walleye

Since 2002, the average Walleye catch rate or catch per unit effort (CPUE) is 16.9 fish/net (both near and off-shore nets combined). The 2020 CPUE was 12.8 fish/net and down from 2019 (18.3 fish/net). The current 3-year average for CPUE is 15.5 fish/net and exceeds the 2018-2023 management goal ~ 14 fish/net. Gill net sampled Walleye ranged in length from 6.4 to 29 inches with an average length of 12.9 inches. Small Walleye (< 11 inches) were above average, while keeper-sized Walleye (14 to 19 inches) were below the historic average. Walleye 12 to 14 inches were well below historic levels and is the result of the 2016 and 2017 year-classes being of moderate strength. Lastly, the 2018-2023 fisheries management plan calls for the annual percentage of gill net sampled Walleye over 20 inches to be 5 to 15% of the total catch. In 2020, over 15% the Walleye sampled were 20 inches or larger.

Sauger

In 2020, Sauger gill net CPUE was 25.7 fish/net and the current 3-year average (24.6 fish/net) exceeds the 2018-2023 management goal of ~ 16 fish/net. Above average Sauger abundance experienced the past few years is the result of strong year-classes being produced in 2011 and from 2014-2016. Year-classes produced in 2018 and 2019 are predicted to be weak and moderate in strength. Sauger sampled in 2020, ranged in length from 3 to 18 inches with an average length of 11 inches. Sauger from 11 to 18 inches are at or exceed historic levels, while fish < 10 inches were below average due to poor recruitment noted in 2018.

Northern Pike

Lake of the Woods is managed for a high-quality Northern Pike population, with a significant component of "trophy" Northern Pike over 40 inches long. To monitor the size structure of the Northern Pike population, it is sampled every 5 years using trap nets at known spawning sites. Trap netting conducted in 2016 and 2017 revealed a high-quality size structure for all sampled tributaries to Lake of the Woods and Rainy River. Fall gill netting in 2020 sampled Northern Pike from 15 to 43 inches with an average length of 24 inches.

Yellow Perch

Yellow Perch are often not targeted by anglers fishing Lake of the Woods, but caught incidentally fishing for Walleye and Sauger. Under the current fisheries management plan for 2018-2023 no population level goals are set for Yellow Perch, but are of management interest. Results from 2020 indicate perch near-shore abundance is below the 10-year average and was the second lowest observed since 2010. Catch rates for Yellow Perch are highly variable, but have slightly declined since the early 1990s. Yellow Perch ranged in length from 5 to nearly 14 inches with an average length of 9 inches.

Lake Sturgeon

Since 2004, spawning Lake Sturgeon are sampled annually on the Rapid River (a tributary to the Rainy River). Over the past 15 years there has been an overall increase in mean length and greater proportion of "large" sturgeon in the sampled population. In addition to obtaining lengths, sampled Lake Sturgeon are tagged with a unique number at the base of the dorsal fin. This information has revealed that males typically spawn every 2 to 3 years (in some cases annually) and females spawn every 4 to 9 years. In total nearly 2,000 fish have been tagged at the Rapid River and over 9,000 have been tagged system-wide since the inception of the tagging program. In addition to natural resource sampling, nearly 200 tag returns are reported annually by anglers. This information provides information on movement patterns, spawning occurrence, growth, and harvest metrics.

In order to harvest a Lake Sturgeon, anglers must purchase a harvest tag. However no tag is required to fish catch-and-release for Lake Sturgeon. Anglers may harvest one Lake Sturgeon per calendar year. A sturgeon must be between 45 and 50 inches (inclusive) or longer than 75 inches to be legal to harvest. All other sturgeon must be immediately released. The Lake Sturgeon harvest season is from April 24 to May 7, and from July 1 to September 30. The catch and release only season is from May 8 to May 15, and from October 1 through April 23. You may not fish for Lake Sturgeon during the closed season (May 16 to June 30).
