Infested Waters Designation

Lake of the Woods and the Rainy River have received an infested waters designation due to the presence of Spiny Water Flea and Zebra Mussel. Spiny Water Flea was first documented in the late 2000s in the Minnesota waters of Lake of the Woods. In 2019, Zebra Mussel veligers (lavae) were sampled by fisheries staff in Muskeg Bay and is the first occurrence of this AIS (aquatic invasive species) in the Minnesota waters of Lake of the Woods. No adult Zebra Mussel were observed in 2020.

At this date, the most immediate impact of Spiny Water Flea has been to human users of the lake and river. Emerald shiner is a popular bait fish on Lake of the Woods. Local bait shops and resorts have had significant businesses harvesting bait within the system. There is concern that Spiny Water Flea eggs may be ingested by small fish, and that Spiny Water Flea may then be spread through the bait fish distribution. To deal with this potential issue, a prohibition against bait collection, by non-permitted individuals, has been enacted. Trained and licensed bait dealers may still collect bait fish from infested waters, but the collected bait must be handled to allow the fish to purge any eggs they may have ingested.

Rusty Crayfish, a native of the Ohio River system, have been established in parts of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods since the late 1960s, but have been present in the Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods only since 2006. At this point Rusty Crayfish are present in fairly low densities, but are continuing to expand south. Last fall they were found from the Northwest Angle, south to Pine Island in addition to the Rainy River. Densities of Rusty Crayfish decline substantially from the Northwest Angle south. Rusty Crayfish have displaced the native crayfish within 2 years of colonizing an area, and have been associated with declines in aquatic vegetation when they become established.

Catch per unit effort of Walleye in 1990 is at the long-term mean (1990-1980) of 12.7 fish per lift. Recruitment appears to be stable as three successive year classes are present in the catch; the strong 1987 year class, and the moderate 1988 and 1989 year classes. Sauger catch per unit effort increased from 1989 due to recruitment of the strong 1989 year class to the index nets. Yellow Perch and White Sucker catch per unit effort is above the long-term (1980-89) mean for both species. Northern Pike catch per unit effort decreased slightly from 1989. The 1990 index netting results indicate that fish populations are stable.

The Lake of the Woods Walleye population is in excellent shape with a variety of age classes represented in fall assessment. The very strong 1987 year class has entered the fishery. This fall's gillnetting effort had the highest catch of young of year Walleye since this program was initiated in 1980. Though the number of young of year Walleye caught in the fall are not a sensitive indicator of year class strength they probably do indicate when a strong year class has been produced. Sauger have a number of year classes represented in the sampling. Northern Pike appear to have had several poor year classes, likely as a result of the past drought. The return to a wet cycle will probably help Northern Pike recruitment. Large Norther Pike remain fairly abundant in fall sampling.

The Walleye population is in very good shape with about 15 age groups represented annually. Walleye from the very strong 1991 year class averaged 17-18 inches in length in the fall gill net assessment. The 1992 and 1993 year classes are weak. This weakness is manifested as a dip in the fall gill net sample length frequency in the 13-16 inch intervals. Based on young of year assessment, year classes produced in 1994 and 1995 are projected to be strong and moderate, respectively. Due to poor growth during the summer of 1996, the 1996 year class is projected to be virtually non-existent.The Sauger population is characterized by highly variable recruitment. This appears to be the norm for Sauger on Lake of the Woods. The portion of the population recruited to the fishery is dominated by the strong year classes produced in 1989 and 1990. The bulk of these fish range from 12 to 14 inches in length in the fall gill net assessment. It appears that the 1993 and 1994 year classes are moderate to moderately strong. Sauger from these year classes range from 9-12 inches, total length, with the peak in the 10 inch interval. The bulk of these Sauger are not of a size that anglers will readily harvest. Unlike Walleye, we have not yet developed a way of predicting year class strength based on young of year sampling.Northern Pike are not sampled very effectively with standard lake assessment gill nets. In the 1983 to 1994 fall gill net assessment, Northern Pike catch per unit effort has ranged from 0.8 to 2.7 with a 10 year average of 1.5. The problem of small sample size has been addressed with a spring survey, using trap nets. Spring trap net spawning run assessment depicts a very high quality Northern Pike population. In 1995 the spawning run assessment was expanded to tag up to 1,500 Northern Pike. The primary purpose of this study was to determine if the population of Northern Pike using streams in Minnesota as spawning sites were an exclusively Minnesota stock or if the stock is shared with the province of Manitoba and/or Ontario. In 1995, 15 percent of 1,432 tagged pike exceeded 30 inches. Approximately two percent of tagged Northern Pike exceeded 40 inches. Preliminary tag return data suggests that the Northern Pike that spawn in Rainy River tributary streams spend their time in the Rainy River and are a distinct stock from the pike that spawn in Lake of the Woods tributaries. Rainy River tributary streams, as a group, have significantly smaller average lengths than any of all of the other sites at which Northern Pike are tagged. Zipple Bay and Warroad River stood out as sites from which a lot of tags were returned. These are areas that have a relatively high proportion of targeted Northern Pike effort.Two creel surveys were conducted on Lake of the Woods this past summer. The annual south shore creel survey monitors summer harvest by anglers based on the south shore of Lake of the Woods, from Baudette to Springsteel Island, just north of Warroad. Neither catch per unit of effort (cpue) nor length frequency of harvested Walleye is available from this creel survey.The primary objective of the northwest angle creel survey is to monitor the harvest of Walleye, by Minnesota based anglers, in the province of Ontario. Ontario would like to restrict the walleye harvest by Minnesota based anglers to 8,000 pounds. The 1995 Ontario harvest of Walleye by Minnesota based anglers was 20,075 pounds. This is a substantial increase in harvest from that measured in 1994 (9,394 pounds). In 1996, Minnesota based anglers harvested 25,396 pounds of walleye in Ontario. The average walleye harvest in Ontario, by Minnesota based anglers, for the three years of the creel survey is 18,288 pounds. I feel that the 1994 harvest was influenced by a lot of negative publicity so anglers, that would normally have fished the area, stayed away. It is reasonable to expect that the average Minnesota based harvest of walleye in Ontario will range from 20,000 to 25,000 pounds in the future. At the 1996 border waters meeting, the Ontario contingent did not indicate if they would pursue any additional restrictions on Minnesota based anglers to try to reduce harvest to the harvest goal. Minnesota based anglers also harvest an average of about 20,000 pounds of walleye from the Minnesota waters of Lake of the Woods.

Physical Description

Lake of the Woods straddles the Canada-United States border, and is shared between the Canadian provinces of Manitoba and Ontario, and the U. S. state of Minnesota. Water level is directly controlled through three hydroelectric dams located at the head of the Winnipeg River in Kenora, Ontario. The Rainy River provides 75% of the inflow to the lake.

The lake is comprised of several distinct basins. Minnesota portion of Lake of the Woods (just over 300,000 acres) lies within Muskeg Bay, Big Traverse Bay and Little Traverse Bay. Big Traverse Bay and Muskeg Bay are largely devoid of bottom structure and islands. Little Traverse Bay is more characteristic of the Ontario portion of Lake of the Woods, with numerous islands and reefs. These three basins do not stratify and in most years have widespread, dense, blue-green algae blooms that are first evident in July and continue through October.

Fisheries Management

In December of 2017, DNR Fisheries in Baudette began a management plan review/revision for Lake of the Woods. Stated within the fisheries management plan is a brief background of management history, series of management goals and objectives and management actions. The plan is effective for five years and goals/objectives will be reevaluated in 2023. New to the process this year, we incorporated a Fisheries Input Group (FIG) to provide perspectives and angler expectations. The FIG included 14 individuals from various parts of the state and representing different interests. In the end, a revised management plan was produced that went out for public input. The final plan can be found at: https://files.dnr.state.mn.us/fisheries/largelakes/low/low_plan.pdf
